{
  "doc_id": "35265",
  "text": "Interest in the role of genome-wide patterns of methylation in human disease has increased in recent years [CITATION_1] . The epigenome, in general, and the methylome, more specifically, have the potential for large effects in disease etiology. DNA methylation has already been associated with many cancers [CITATION_2] , and different cell types are known to differ in their methylation patterns. Illumina has been developing genome-wide methylation arrays that enable epigenome-wide association studies of human disease [CITATION_3] . These arrays are based on BeadChip technology, and the most recent ones contain probes for over 480K CpG sites. These sites cover 99% of RefSeq genes with multiple probes per gene, and 96% of CpG islands from the UCSC database.",
